'''Saif Ali Khan''' ({{IPA|hns|ˈsæːf əˈli xaːn|pron}}; born '''Sajid Ali Khan Pataudi'''; 16 August 1970)<ref>{{cite news|title=Saif-Kareena wedding: Saif gets married as Sajid Ali Khan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Saif-Kareena-wedding-Saif-gets-married-as-Sajid-Ali-Khan/articleshow/16835439.cms|date=16 October 2012|access-date=18 October 2012|work=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909165613/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Saif-Kareena-wedding-Saif-gets-married-as-Sajid-Ali-Khan/articleshow/16835439.cms|archive-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> is an Indian actor and film producer who primarily works in [[Hindi cinema|Hindi]] and [[Telugu cinema|Telugu films]] The current head of the [[Pataudi family]] and the 10th titular [[Nawab of Pataudi]]<ref>{{Cite news |date=2011-11-01 |title=Saif Ali Khan is now the 10th Nawab of Pataudi |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Saif-Ali-Khan-is-now-the-10th-Nawab-of-Pataudi/articleshow/10562215.cms |access-date=2025-01-17 |work=The Times of India |issn=0971-8257}}</ref>, he is the son of actress [[Sharmila Tagore]] and cricketer [[Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi]]. Khan has won [[List of awards and nominations received by Saif Ali Khan|several awards]], including a [[National Film Awards|National Film Award]] and seven [[Filmfare Awards]], and received the [[Padma Shri]], the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of India|fourth highest Indian civilian]] award in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aamir, Rahman to receive Padma Bhushan; Padma Shree for Rekha, Saif|website=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/award/filmfare-award/2010-2/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128214849/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2010/01/25/13696/index.html|archive-date=28 January 2010|date=25 January 2010|url-status=live|access-date=1 October 2011}}</ref> 

Khan made his acting debut in ''[[Parampara (1993 film)|Parampara]]'' (1993), and had success in the multi-starrers ''[[Yeh Dillagi]]'' (1994), ''[[Main Khiladi Tu Anari]]'' (1994), ''[[Kachche Dhaage]]'' (1999) and ''[[Hum Saath-Saath Hain]]'' (1999). In the 2000s, he gained praise and won multiple awards for his roles in the romantic comedies ''[[Dil Chahta Hai]]'' (2001) and ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' (2003), and had success as a solo male star in the romances ''[[Hum Tum (film)|Hum Tum]]'' (2004), ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'', ''[[Salaam Namaste]]'' (both 2005) and ''[[Ta Ra Rum Pum]]'' (2007).

Khan also earned critical acclaim for playing a manipulative businessman in ''[[Ek Hasina Thi (film)|Ek Hasina Thi]]'' (2004), an apprentice in the English film ''[[Being Cyrus]]'' (2006) and the [[Iago]] character in ''[[Omkara (2006 film)|Omkara]]'' (2006). He had further commercial success in the action thrillers ''[[Race (2008 film)|Race]]'' (2008) and ''[[Race 2]]'' (2013), and the romantic comedies ''[[Love Aaj Kal (2009 film)|Love Aaj Kal]]'' (2009) and ''[[Cocktail (2012 film)|Cocktail]]'' (2012). Between another string of under-performing ventures, Khan was appreciated for headlining [[Netflix]]'s first original Indian series ''[[Sacred Games (TV series)|Sacred Games]]'' (2018–2019) and had his highest-grossing releases in the action films ''[[Tanhaji]]'' (2020) and ''[[Devara: Part 1]]'' (2024).

Khan has been noted for [[Saif Ali Khan filmography|his roles]] in a range of film genres—from crime dramas to action thrillers and comic romances. In addition to film acting, Khan is a frequent television presenter, stage show performer, and the owner of the production companies Illuminati Films and Black Knight Films.

